brewery.brewery_description: A. Le Coq is the oldest and largest beverage company in Estonia. Founded in 1826 and owned by Finnish Olvi, A. Le Coq is known for its flagship beer A. Le Coq Premium, the most popular beer in Estonia.

beer.beer_description: The bock-type beer has been brewed for centuries in Europe. The light Double Bock is the first of its kind in Estonia. It has a pleasantly mellow taste for its alcohol content that makes Double Bock a powerful but cool beer. The recipe and taste distinctions of Double Bock have been developed taking into account the current taste preferences of Estonian consumers.

Saaremaa Tuulik is available with an ABV of 4.7%, 5.0%, and 5.2%.

Saaremaa Tuulik is a lager with a strong taste. This beer has been beloved by the visitors of this island as well as by its natives. Legend says that already in the ancient times people used to bring home barrels of Saaremaa Tuulik when visiting the island.

Saaremaa Tuulik –  a favorite from Saaremaa since times immemorial.

INGREDIENTS:
beer (water, barley malt, wheat malt, barley, hops, hop extracts), water, cherry juice (15%) from concentrated juice, sugar, carbon dioxide, carrot concentrate, acidity regulator – citric acid, cherry flavour, preservative – sodium benzoate.
Produced specially for AS Tallink Grupp

Imperial Gold is a premium lager with a rich and full-bodied taste. The valuable malt delivered from Scotland gives it a deep golden colour and a thick head.  The taste and appearance of A. Le Coq Imperial Gold are as worthy of royal attention today as they ever were.
Traditsiooniline Saksa nisuõlu.

In 1912. A. Le Coq was chosen as the official supplier of the Russian emperor's court, and Imperial Extra Double Stout, which was brewed in Tartu, became available throughout the empire.
We have launched A. Le Coq Imperial again to show respect for our old traditions. The Imperial range is for beer lovers with exquisite taste.
   
Imperial Ale is a top-fermented beer with a rich flavour bouquet. There is a perfect balance between the delicious bitter taste of hops and the sweetness of malt.  The copper colour that characterizes the best ales adds a respectability referring to its imperial past.
